okay back to work, share thoughts. mind was wondering about this for some reason. 

/fin
more than just hearing it, there was some sort of conditioning beyond simple repetition. a reward system at play maybe, some incentives or punishment for not believing this wrong thing.

when it's the truth, you simply had the truth drilled into your head, like you did if you were good at math or boxing or whatever, playing the piano, among other things.

if it's not true, i think it's more accurately brainwashing. you heard something over and over

or "you're brainwashed into being a good golfer or boxer."

really we are getting at the idea that what they believe does not line up with reality, according to somebody. 

i think about how propaganda is described often as "brainwashing."

a couple times in my life i took a great liking to math. in undergrad i used to go to the math lab daily and work on homework and extra homework and usually got near perfect scores on exams. nobody would say "wow you got brainwashed into being good at trig."

how do you get good at boxing or golf? do the same move over and over and over, thousands of times.

when you learned to solve say a some math equation, from basic addition to high-level math, you didn't do it one time. you did it over and over again.

being brainwashed implies a level of repetition, not something you heard merely once and thought "oh wow that's it!"

but repetition on its own is the basis of skill in many ways. You can recall and recognize something the more times you've done or heard it.
